    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Pinna squamifera</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_995",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Very large, fragile, pale-brown bivalve with marked longitudinal rows of external scale-like cusps that run the length of each shell. Shells gape widely at the posterior (upper) end, which projects from the substratum. An elongate hinge ligament joins the shells along dorsal margin and a dense bunch of long byssal threads projects from the ventral margin anchoring the shell to pebbles and other nearly objects.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_996",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Very large, reaching 390 mm shell length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_997",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Saldanha Bay to about East London.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_998",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Lives partially buried in the sand in sheltered sites at depth of up to about 35 m with the posterior (broad and gaping) end of the shell projecting into the water. Often densely overgrown with fouling organisms, such that each mussel acts as a small ‘island’ supporting a community of smaller hard-substratum organisms. The commensal crab <i>Pinnotheres dolfeini</i> is commonly found on the gills and steals food from the mussel. The elongate byssal threads of similar horse mussels in the Mediterranean were once woven into a strong and highly prized cloth thought, for example, to have been used to weave Jason’s Golden Fleece of Greek mythology. Dead shells, or pieces of shell, are often washed ashore after storms and have a beautiful shiny internal nacreous layer. Pearls are also sometimes produced.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_999",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": [
                {
                    "text": "<p>Byssal threads have been used to weave Jason’s Golden Fleece of Greek mythology.</p>",
                    "altText": "",
                    "title": "",
                    "imageUrl": {
                        "1x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-2899-250.webp",
                        "2x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-2899-500.webp",
