                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>All bivalves feed by drawing water in then filtering it through the enlarged sieve-like gills. Food particles filtered from the water are transported by cilia to the ventral edge of the gill and then forward to the mouth.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_1000",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": [
                {
                    "text": "",
                    "altText": "",
                    "title": "",
                    "imageUrl": {
                        "1x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-2896-250.webp",
                        "2x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-2896-500.webp",
                        "4x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-2896-1000.webp"
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Details unknown, but almost all bivalves are broadcast spawners.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_1001",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Unlikely to be confused with any other regional species due to its large size and marked external scales. Replaced on more tropical eastern parts of South Africa by the furrowed horse-mussel <i>Pinna muricata,</i> which has smaller external cusps and a distinct furrow running down the inner surface in the centre of each valve. Early records of <i>A. squamifera</i> from the east coast are misidentifications of <i>P. muricata</i>.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_1002",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
